<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT 466 / DT 570 / HT 570 Service Manual - 2004 Emissions with EGR - Flywheel and Flywheel Housing - Removal
        - Crankshaft Timing Disk and Rear Oil Seal
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc graphiccount="3">
        <title>Crankshaft Timing Disk and Rear Oil Seal</title>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>To avoid engine damage, if only replacing the timing disk, do not use bolts to remove timing disk
                    from crankshaft. Damage to the rear oil seal could occur resulting in a leak.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2651313" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH06/H06002.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Removing the crankshaft timing disk</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use an H-bar puller to remove the crankshaft timing disk from the end of the crankshaft .
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2651314" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH06/H06003.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Drilling holes in the rear oil seal</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Use appropriate size drill bit for pulling screw.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Drill two holes of appropriate diameter for slide hammer use into the rear oil seal at
                approximately the 3 and 9 o'clock positions.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2651315" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH06/H06004.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Removing the rear oil seal</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a
                <hotlnk document="eges2651_269.xml" xrefid="t13003" appearance="hottext">slide hammer</hotlnk>
                to alternately pull on each side of the rear oil seal using the two previously drilled holes. Discard
                oil seal assembly.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
